recordings.file-name: XC601906-Carolina Wren vocalization in the rain.mp3
recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: The fact that is was raining is significant only to the extent that the bird - and only this bird - was active at the time.  I characterize this as 'cheer', produced by the male in response to my presence in the doorway to the garage where I stood with recorder in hand.  Carolina Wrens are notorious for attempting to nest, and post-breeding take shelter, in these openings, so I assume it treated my presence as a predator or a hinderance. This is consistent with researchers' explanation of this vocalization.  That said, this species is apparently known for geographic dialects of this sound  as well as others.

recordings.rmk: On 5 of 8 days I sneaked a tiny microphone into a hanging basket on my deck where Carolina Wrens had built a nest. I was going to add a sixth day, but they fledged! Throughout the recording you can hear the nestlings rustling around in the leaves and pine straw of the nest. On day 1 they emit a begging call consistently, even without the presence of a parent. Thereafter they remain quiet until the parent signals his or her approach with a single chip note. Each day the begging of two chicks increases in volume. This particularly noticeable in the last segment. There will be a fade of 3 to 5 seconds between days.

A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

recordings.rmk: One of my favorite wren recordings, continues to fascinate me. First a very close male starts singing one song type twice, then switches to another song type. Then a farther-away male starts to sing type II exactly as did the closer male. Then the close male starts singing song type II again, while the farther male starts singing song type I. Then "cheer" alarm calls start from farther away, while the close male is still singing song type II. I suspect it is the farther male. At the end, the close male throws in a third type.
